## Test Anti-Pattern Audit: `ProductCatalogTests.cs`

### Summary

**10 tests reviewed · 6 Critical · 1 Medium · 0 Low**

This test class is a textbook **coverage-touching** suite. Every public method on `ProductCatalog` is called — giving you the 95% coverage number — but almost nothing is actually verified. These tests will stay green even if every method silently returns wrong data, corrupts state, or stops working entirely.

---

### 🔴 Critical — False Confidence

#### 1. Coverage Touching (Systemic)

All 10 tests methodically walk the public API surface of `ProductCatalog` in declaration order. Six of them have **zero assertions**; three more use only `Assert.IsNotNull`, which merely confirms "something was returned." This is the exact pattern you described: every method is hit for coverage, nothing is verified.

**Tests with zero assertions (4):**

| Line | Method | What it misses |
|------|--------|----------------|
| 17 | `AddProduct_Works` | Never checks the product was actually stored |
| 33 | `UpdatePrice_Works` | Never checks the price actually changed |
| 39 | `RemoveProduct_Works` | Never checks the product was actually removed |
| 68 | `ApplyBulkDiscount_Works` | Never checks prices were actually reduced |
| 64 | `GetProductCount_Works` | Doesn't even capture the return value |
| 85 | `ImportFromCsv_Works` | Never checks any product was actually imported |

**Fix — example for `AddProduct_Works` (line 17):**
```csharp
// BEFORE — touches code, verifies nothing
[TestMethod]
public void AddProduct_Works()
{
    var product = new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m);
    _catalog.AddProduct(product);
}

// AFTER — verifies observable behavior
[TestMethod]
public void AddProduct_ProductIsRetrievable()
{
    var product = new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m);
    _catalog.AddProduct(product);

    var retrieved = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
    Assert.AreEqual("Widget", retrieved?.Name);
    Assert.AreEqual(9.99m, retrieved?.Price);
}
```

**Fix — `UpdatePrice_Works` (line 33):**
